Elder Research Project

Thomas Wileman

March 20, 2019

github repository

Findings: The data included a field called App_result. Whenever this result was greater than or equal to seven the ASD_YES feature equaled 1. This flaw in the data meant that all the questionaire data could be used to determine whether or not the user indicated they were on the autism spectrum.

Analysis

Set directory, load dataset, and install most of the packages needed for the data.

Initial exploratory analysis led to the following findings: - 704 observations / 21 features (9 discrete, 12 continuous) - Question marks masked missing data - Data was missing from Age, Ethnicity, and Relation columns - There was one outlier in the Age column (likely mistyped information) - Age_desc is the same for each observation - Many of the character observations contain special characters or white space - App_result is highly correlated with ASD

##   rows columns discrete_columns continuous_columns all_missing_columns
## 1  704      21               10                 11                   0
##   total_missing_values complete_rows total_observations memory_usage
## 1                    0           704              14784       100752

To clean data, first replace all question marks with NA.

# Question marks in original data were used in place of NA
data[data == "?"] <- NA

Next, correct the identified outlier in the age column. ID the outlier using the IQR, replace it with the median.

# Remove outlier age, replace it with the median then replace NA values with mean
x <- as.numeric(data$Age)
qnt <- quantile(x, probs=c(.25, .75), na.rm = T)
caps <- quantile(x, probs=c(.05, .95), na.rm = T)
H <- 1.5 * IQR(data$Age, na.rm = T)
x[x > (qnt[2] + H)] <- median(data$Age)
data$Age <- (x)

Then, replace missing ages with the mean age.

#Impute the mean age
data$Age <- as.numeric(data$Age)
data$Age[is.na(data$Age)] = mean(data$Age, na.rm = TRUE)

Moving to Relation. I struggled with this but decided to replace it with the most frequent observation, Self (88%).

#Impute most frequent factor into relation
data$Relation[is.na(data$Relation)] <- "Self"

The next step is removing special characters and white space from character features.

#Remove special characterers from country of residence, ethnicity, and relation
special.characters <- "a1~!@#$%^&*(){}_+:\"<>?,./;'[]-=" 
data$Country_of_res <- str_replace_all(data$Country_of_res, "[[:punct:]]", "")
data$Ethnicity <- str_replace_all(data$Ethnicity, "[[:punct:]]", "")
data$Relation <- str_replace_all(data$Relation, "[[:punct:]]", "")
data$Age_desc <- str_replace_all(data$Age_desc, "[[:punct:]]", "")
data$Country_of_res <- trimws(data$Country_of_res)
data$Ethnicity <- trimws(data$Ethnicity)
data$Relation <- trimws(data$Relation)
data$Age_desc <- trimws(data$Age_desc)

For ethnicity, replace missing values with the ethnicity most frequently reported in the corresponding country of residence. For the remaining missing values (10), replace with the most common observation, WhiteEuropean (35%). A better option would be to incorporate region and follow a similiar technique or impute from a distribution.

# Impute unknown ethnicities with most frequent ethnicity from country of residence
data.region.ethnicity <- filter(data, !is.na(Ethnicity))
data.region.ethnicity <- subset(data.region.ethnicity, select = c("Ethnicity", "Country_of_res")) 
max.table <- data.region.ethnicity %>%
  group_by(Country_of_res) %>%
  count(Ethnicity, Country_of_res) %>%
  filter(n == max(n))
data$Ethnicity[is.na(data$Ethnicity)] <- max.table$Ethnicity[match(data$Country_of_res, max.table$Country_of_res)][which(is.na(data$Ethnicity))]
data$Ethnicity[is.na(data$Ethnicity)] <- "WhiteEuropean"

Modify data for logistic regression and SVM modeling.

data.clean <- data
data.clean <- drop_columns(data.clean, "Age_desc")
data.clean$Age <- as.integer(data.clean$Age)
data.clean$Gender <- ifelse(data.clean$Gender == "m", 0, 1)
data.clean$Ethnicity <- as.factor(data.clean$Ethnicity)
data.clean$Jundice <- ifelse(data.clean$Jundice == "yes", 1, 0)
data.clean$Family <- ifelse(data.clean$Family == "yes", 1, 0)
data.clean$Country_of_res <- as.factor(data.clean$Country_of_res)
data.clean$App_result <- as.integer(data.clean$App_result)
data.clean$ASD <- ifelse(data.clean$ASD == "YES", 1, 0)

Split data for training and testing.

set.seed(100)
train <- sample(nrow(data.clean), 0.8*nrow(data.clean), replace = FALSE)
TrainSet <- data.clean[train,]
ValidSet <- data.clean[-train,]

Stepwise regression to identify important features. First regresses questionaire answers (including interactions) on ASD (target variable). It appears that a positive answer for each question is indicative of an ASD symptom. This is supported by the observation that any app_result >= 7 results in a positive ASD result.

Second regresses demographic information on ASD. I did this in hope of identifying what demographic features might corre

data.Forest <- data
data.Forest$ASD <- as.factor(data.Forest$ASD)
data.Forest <- drop_columns(data.Forest, "Age_desc")
data.Forest$Age <- as.factor(data.Forest$Age)
data.Forest$Gender <- as.factor(data.Forest$Gender)
data.Forest$Ethnicity <- as.factor(data.Forest$Ethnicity)
data.Forest$Jundice <- as.factor(data.Forest$Jundice)
data.Forest$Family <- as.factor(data.Forest$Family)
data.Forest$Country_of_res <- as.factor(data.Forest$Country_of_res)
data.Forest$App_result <- as.factor(data.Forest$App_result)
data.Forest$Used_app_before <- as.factor(data.Forest$Used_app_before)
data.Forest$Relation <- as.factor(data.Forest$Relation)

train.forest <- sample(nrow(data.Forest), 0.8*nrow(data.Forest), replace = FALSE)
